ur of the public spaces of gentrified Brooklyn deepens our understanding of how these women use their collective lives to combat the isolation felt during the workday as a domestic worker.Though at first glance these childcare providers appear isolated and exploited-and this is the case for many-Mose Brown shows that their daily interactions in the social spaces they create allow their collective lives and cultural identities to flourish. Raising Brooklyn demonstrates how these daily interactions form a continuous expression of cultural preservation as a weapon against difficult working conditions, examining how this process unfolds through the use of cell phones, food sharing, and informal economic systems. Ultimately, Raising Brooklyn places the organization of domestic workers within the framework of a social justice movement, creating a dialogue between workers who don’t believe their exploitative work conditions will change and an organization whose members believe change can come about through public displays of solidarity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNanniesxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aNannieszNew York (State)zBrooklyn. 0aNannieszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aNannies. 0aPublic spacesxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aPublic spaceszNew York (State)zBrooklyn. 0aPublic spaceszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aPublic spaces. 0aWest IndiansxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aWest IndianszNew York (State)zBrooklyn. 0aWest IndianszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aWest Indians. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aBrooklyn.  aRaising.  achildcare.  achildren.  adaily.  aexamining.  afamilies.  ahelp.  aimportant.  ain-depth.  alives.  alook.  aoffers.  aplay.  aproviders.  araise.  aroles.  athese.  athey.  awhose.08iTitle is part of eBook 